content.description: Stand start and grab nice holds til you suddenly have to move far. Half mantle and enjoy a casual top out.  A bit of reach is nice for this one.
content.protection: a pad or two. A spotter is nice for the tree.
content.location: on the way to cheesecake, across from bucket

content.description: Sit start on lowest pinches.
content.location: Phantom

content.description: Underclings to the left of Solar Flare start. Move right into Solar Flare and finish up.
content.location: Left and low to Solar Flare

content.description: Start low on crimps, make your way up and left on positive slopers.
content.location: Looking at Razor's Edge, the boulder to the right. The climb starts low to the left of the large off-width.

climbs.name: Rhino Low
climbs.fa: Either Andrew Gross or Alex Savage?

content.description: Start in the cave as far back as possible. Use obvious jug crimp to start and traverse left into Rhino. Climb Rhino into the hole, perform some awkward moves to bust out of the hole onto the face. Make a committing move to the high ridge and traverse right to top.
content.location: From the parking lot follow the main trail to the first main break left (short round rock on left). Pass a few tall blocks, and before the first main maze corridor rhino is on the left.

content.description: Start left side of cave and work some tension moves on roof and arete to a big left hand throw to good hold on face. Get situated in the human sized hueco, then work out the top.I've heard sit start is the true way, but the stand start with right hand on bad side pull at the base of the roof, left hand good pocket on face seemed to get the grade, in my opinion.Starting way back in the cave on the right, goes at around v10.
content.protection: Special note: the roof is the perfect height to accidentally slam the back of your head on when standing up.
content.location: Take left at first fork from parking lot, walk a minute or two past trailside tears, then look left for large hueco in cliffline 15 or so yards off the main trail. Same boulder as Jug Roof.

content.description: Sit start on jugs and traverse left to the razor fin
content.location: Phantom

content.description: Amazing looking thin arête right side of the main boulder
content.location: Hike down from the parking lot, staying right at the only split in the trail. Follow trail till you hit the obvious, three pointed boulder covered in amazing problems

content.description: Nice line that starts on the block at the base of the roof. Work your way up the obvious feature to the left. Continue left across the roof and top out on the pebbly side. Be careful not to dab on the tree.
content.location: As you enter Zahnd, head left at the fork at the beginning of the trail. Continue on the main trail. You will reach a corridor with tall boulders. Go through that corridor. On the other side a large boulder just up the hill to the left can be seen. That's it.

content.description: Start on the low Turret start with double undercling sloper jug. Traverse right into and finish up Razor's Edge. A little bit of a but dragger but the moves are cool and at least you get to climb Razor's Edge again.
content.location: Low left start to Razor's Edge.

content.description:
Same start as Harvest Moon. Instead of making the last move, moves out right to a sloper and tops out to the right.Grade seems pretty reach dependent. V9 in guidebook but definitely easier if you have a 5’10”+ reach

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n4fWECu5_a4
Start same as Harvest Moon. Move left into some under clings then straight up to a slopey top out.
content.location: Phantom area

content.description: Sit start on low pockets, traverse up and right on lip of boulder. Top out on jugs on tip of boulder. Top of boulder is OFF until top-out.
content.location: From the parking lot, follow main trail and turn left at the first intersection. Follow trail until reaching the obvious boulder jutting diagonally out of the ground.

content.description: appropriately named
content.location: middle blocks area, hard to miss

content.description: Are you the person that always brings a rope and rack? Do you love arnold schwarzenegger references or just listening to the clink of gear and disappointed whispers of boulderers as you carry a rack into a boulder field?  Is it freesoloing instead of a highball if it's done without rope now? I dunno but it was pretty fun to climb and took great gear. It's just kinda short.
content.protection: Standard southern rack. No anchor, rap off tree.
content.location: When there are tall rocks on both sides of you on the way in, its on your right.

content.description: Start on tooth sidepull, move up and right to an undercling, then use two more crimps to set up for the lunge to the jug at the lip. Slopers lead to the top.Would love to know if anyone knows what climb this is or if it has been done
content.protection: Pads and spotter, there is a large log in the landing area
content.location: 15ish feet to the left of "Out of Time". Starts on obvious tooth sidepull in roof and follows a pretty straight line.

content.description: Stand start and up to the jugs
content.location: Land of the aretes

content.description: Start on jug and go straight up
content.location: Middle blocs

content.description: Sit start and traverse left
content.location: Middle blocs

content.description: Sit start low and to the right of the normal starthttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Yr3G-QerOU
Classic. Begin matched in the vertical slot, and make a big move to a sloper rail. Set up and huck for the lip. Top out straight up.
content.location: Starts low in the obvious vertical pod on the left side of the main boulder at phantom.

content.description: Step up on the mossy ledge wipe your shoes again and crimp up to a good sloper up top. We never hit the ledge falling?
content.location: On the way to cheesecake arete, look to the right, it is the penultimate rock before cheesecake.

content.description: SDS low on a left crimp and right pocket. Climb left side of the pocketed arete. Keep close or you'll fall (and probably dab)
content.protection: two pads covers the landing and the boulder behind you
content.location: In the land of aretes, this line has a boulder just to the side and behind it. You'll notice a large namesake hole near the top of the boulder

content.description: Sit start 5 feet below and right of Razor's Edge start on left hand undercling and right hand low sidepull. Make a move or two into Razor's Edge and finish up the beautiful feature.There seems to be some confusion between this one and Razor Burn. It looks like Chatt Bloc might have accidentally been right this time.
content.location: Low right start of Razor's Edge.

content.description: Around the fin arete
content.location: Phantom

content.description: Sit start and climb up
content.location: Middle Blocs

content.description: Stand start and go up
Climb the arete
content.location: Land of the aretes

content.description: Sit start under the roof and climb up
content.location: Congo

content.description: Stand start, hug the arete and make long moves up to the top.
content.location: Land of aretes, just past grab it by the percy and across from tree fort

content.description: Cool, powerful roof climbing on big jugs. Turn the lip and manage the sloper top out.
content.location: Located in the The Wave area

content.description: Don't be fooled by the grade, Full Moon is "V-Next Level" as the book suggests. Climb up and sit in the hole.
content.location: Land of Aretes

content.description: Beautiful area in Walker County, Georgia, on Lookout Mtn. Dense forest with lots of rock scattered about. Characteristically grey and many of the blocs are very pebbly. Very rural area around.
